# How to use user-account

The user-account lib is the **foundation** of the auth stack. It owns `DB_Account` (user/service accounts), `DB_Session` (JWT-backed sessions), and the middleware that validates requests. All other auth methods (password, SAML, OAuth, passkey) depend on user-account — they resolve to an account and create sessions through it.

| Package | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| `@nu-art/user-account-shared` | `DB_Account` and `DB_Session` entities, `API_UserAccount` definition, header constants (`HeaderKey_DeviceId`, `HeaderKey_TabId`) |
| `@nu-art/user-account-backend` | `ModuleBE_AccountDB` (CRUD, `findOrCreateByEmail`, account lifecycle dispatchers), `ModuleBE_SessionDB` (JWT creation/validation/rotation, session middleware, `CollectSessionData`), `ModuleBE_JWT` |
| `@nu-art/user-account-frontend` | `ModuleFE_Account` (device/tab ID management, session claims access), `ModuleFE_Session` (JWT storage, session key accessors), `StorageKey_DeviceId`, `Component_AccountThumbnail`, `PopUp_AccountMenu` |

---

## What you must know

- **User-account does not authenticate.** It stores accounts and sessions. Authentication methods (password, SAML, passkey, OAuth) live in separate libraries that depend on user-account.
- **Session creation is centralized.** All auth methods create sessions via `ModuleBE_SessionDB._session.create` (returns `DB_Session`) or `_session.create.andReturn` (also sets the JWT on the HTTP response header). Never create sessions any other way.
- **`BaseSessionClaims`** is the minimum JWT payload: `{ accountId, deviceId, label }`. Additional claims are collected via the `CollectSessionData` interface.
- **`CollectSessionData` is the extension point.** Any module can implement `CollectSessionData<TypedKeyValue<key, value>>` to inject custom claims into every JWT. The dispatcher runs during `_session.create`. Example: password auth adds `hasPassword`; the account module adds the full `DB_Account` object under the `account` key.
- **Session middleware** (`ModuleBE_SessionDB.Middleware`) validates the JWT, locates the session, rotates if needed, and sets memory keys (`MemKey_AccountId`, `MemKey_DB_Session`, `MemKey_SessionData`). It runs before every authenticated API handler.
- **Account middleware** (`ModuleBE_AccountDB.Middleware`) reads the account from session claims and sets `MemKey_AccountEmail`, `MemKey_AccountId`, `MemKey_AccountType`. Runs after session middleware.
- **`findOrCreateByEmail`** is the primary account resolution for login flows. It looks up by email; if not found, creates a new account. It runs in a transaction and dispatches `__onNewUserRegistered` or `__onUserLogin` accordingly.
- **`StorageKey_DeviceId`** (frontend) generates and persists a unique device ID in localStorage. Every auth method must include this in login requests. It withstands localStorage deletion.
- **Session rotation** is automatic. When a JWT passes `rotationFactor` (default: 50%) of its TTL, the middleware refreshes it transparently. The new JWT is set on the response header.
- **Config** — `ModuleBE_SessionDB` accepts: `sessionTTLms` (default: 1 day), `rotationFactor` (default: 0.5), `maxPrevSession` (default: 10), `jwtSigner.secretKey` (default: `'jwt-signer--account-session'`).

